{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"57da1cc3-a342-4d6e-a35a-4d659b10cb23","content":"Here's the workflow. Now the key steps to complete the setup:\n\n---\n\n### 1. NuGet.org — Register a Trusted Publisher\n\nGo to **nuget.org → Manage Packages → Your Package → Trusted Publishers** (or set it up when first pushing the package) and add:\n\n| Field | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Repository owner | `myorg` |\n| Repository name | `mylib` |\n| Workflow filename | `publish.yml` |\n| Environment | `nuget-publish` |\n\n### 2. GitHub — Create the Environment\n\nGo to **github.com/myorg/mylib → Settings → Environments** and create an environment named **`nuget-publish`**. Optionally add reviewers or branch protection rules.\n\n### 3. How It Works\n\n- No API key anywhere — the workflow uses `id-token: write` to get an OIDC token from GitHub.\n- NuGet.org verifies the token matches the trusted publisher config (repo + workflow + environment).\n- `dotnet nuget push` works without `--api-key` because NuGet.org accepts the OIDC identity.\n\n### 4. Trigger\n\nCreate a GitHub Release → the workflow runs → the package is pushed to nuget.org.\n\n---\n\nThe workflow file is at `.github/workflows/publish.yml`. Want me to adjust anything (e.g., different trigger, .NET version, or multi-project support)?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"80d21a26-061d-4e89-a7f4-25cde5df9152","outputTokens":334,"requestId":"F02C:B0AF0:264192F:2B084DA:69EB4C2B"},"id":"4f97d929-46cd-486f-863f-3a11350f2d03","timestamp":"2026-04-24T10:55:48.151Z","parentId":"df4c19a6-e070-40ec-a985-ea601ef9d5f0"}
